Assignment No. 2

Overview
Exposed all three applications (nginx, httpbin, echoserver) using Envoy Gateway with the Kubernetes Gateway API. Implemented host-based routing, path-based routing, URL rewrite, header injection, request timeout, retry policy, and rate limiting, and verified each one using curl.
Applications Exposed
Host	Backend
web.company.local	nginx
api.company.local	httpbin
test.company.local	echoserver
Implementation Details
•	Installed Envoy Gateway (v1.8.2) via its Helm chart into the envoy-gateway-system namespace; confirmed GatewayClass eg was Accepted: True.
•	Created a Gateway resource (company-gateway) with a single HTTP listener on port 80, hostname *.company.local.
•	Created three HTTPRoute resources (company-route, api-route, test-route), one per hostname, attached to company-gateway.
•	On api-route, added a dedicated rule for /orders implementing: 
o	Path-based routing — matched via PathPrefix: /orders
o	URL rewrite — rewritten to httpbin's /anything endpoint
o	Header injection — added X-Gateway-Source and X-Route headers
o	Request timeout — request: 5s, backendRequest: 3s
•	Created a BackendTrafficPolicy (api-retry-policy) attached to api-route — 3 retries on 5xx/reset/connect-failure, with backoff.
•	Created a BackendTrafficPolicy (test-rate-limit-policy) attached to test-route — local rate limiting at 10 requests/minute.
•	Verified every behavior with curl against the live Gateway.
Problems Faced & How I Solved Them
1. Gateway stuck at Programmed: False (AddressNotAssigned)
The Envoy Gateway Service came up as type: LoadBalancer, and kind has no cloud load-balancer controller, so EXTERNAL-IP stayed <pending> forever. I confirmed via kubectl describe gateway that this was cosmetic — the listener itself was Accepted/ResolvedRefs: True with all 3 routes attached — so I bypassed it using kubectl port-forward directly to the Envoy Service instead of waiting on an external IP.
2. docker ps / kind get clusters couldn't see my running cluster
Diagnosed this as a Docker context mismatch — my active context was default (a local dockerd socket) instead of desktop-linux (Docker Desktop's actual engine, which is what kind had used to create the cluster). Confirmed with docker context ls and switched using docker context use desktop-linux. kubectl itself was unaffected throughout, since it talks via kubeconfig, not the Docker CLI.
3. Port-forward failed with "address already in use" on 8080
Port 8080 was already occupied locally by Jenkins. Rather than stop Jenkins, I just used a different local port for the forward (18080:80), which avoided the conflict entirely.
4. BackendTrafficPolicy rejected with unknown field "spec.rateLimit.local.defaultLimit"
The CRD schema differs by Envoy Gateway version — defaultLimit isn't valid on v1.8.2. Fixed by removing that field; the rules list alone acts as the effective limit.
5. Retry policy looked unverified from logs (only 2 of 4 expected attempts showed up)
httpbin runs 2 replicas, and Envoy load-balances every retry attempt across both pods — but kubectl logs deploy/httpbin only tails one pod by default. Fixed by tailing both pods together with a label selector (kubectl logs -l app=httpbin --prefix), which surfaced all 4 attempts (1 original + 3 retries) across the two pods.
Approach Used
Rather than implementing every feature redundantly on every route, I distributed the 7 required behaviors across the 3 routes in a way that each is demonstrated clearly at least once — host-based routing on all three routes (all resolve to distinct backends by Host header), and path routing/rewrite/header injection/timeout concentrated on api-route (since httpbin has convenient test endpoints like /anything, /delay/{n}, /status/{code} purpose-built for this), retry on api-route, and rate limiting on test-route. This kept the YAML readable while still proving the underlying Gateway API/Envoy Gateway mechanism works identically regardless of which route it's attached to.
